%I A119240 #41 May 12 2026 08:49:45
%S A119240 1,945,1018976683725,1853070540093840001956842537745897243375
%N A119240 Least odd number k such that sigma(k)/k >= n.
%C A119240 These numbers are a subset of the oddly superabundant numbers, A119239. Laatsch mentions a(3). Pettigrew computes a(4) and a(5), the latter being a 123-digit number.
%C A119240 Pettigrew (link, Tableau 5, p. 21) gives a(5) as 3^6*5^4*7^3*11^2*13^2*17^2*19*...*277. - _Jeppe Stig Nielsen_, Jul 03 2017
%C A119240 Student Team in Semboku high school (Y.Nagamichi, Y.Yatera, H.Nakamoto, S.Haruki, K.Yamashita, K.Fujiwara, R.Sogo, Y.Uenishi) gives a(6) as 3^7*5^5*7^4*11^3*13^2*17^2*...*41^2*43*47*53*...*853 (375-digit, 1851th oddly superabundant number). - _Hiroyuki Ogawa_, May 01 2026
%H A119240 Hiroyuki Ogawa, <a href="/A119240/b119240.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..6</a> (a(2),a(3):Richard Laatsch, a(4),a(5):Steve Pettigrew, a(6):Student Team in Semboku High School)
%H A119240 Richard Laatsch, <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/2690424">Measuring the abundancy of integers</a>, Mathematics Magazine 59 (2) (1986) 84-92.
%H A119240 Takeshi Matsunaga, <a href="https://semboku-h.ed.jp/ssh/2026/04/25/2026-04-24%e4%b8%96%e7%95%8c%e5%88%9d%ef%bc%81%e6%b3%89%e5%8c%97%e9%ab%98%e6%a0%a156%e6%9c%9f%e7%94%9f%e6%95%b0%e5%ad%a6%e7%8f%ad%e3%81%8c%e6%9c%80%e5%b0%8f%e3%81%ae%e5%a5%87%e6%95%b06%e5%80%8d/">World first! Semboku High School 56th graduating class mathematics group discovers the smallest odd number with an abundant index greater than 6!</a>, Semboku Science Lab, April 24, 2026.
